Elon Musk resigns as chairman of Tesla’s board of directors
The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission and Tesla founder Elon Musk have settled their dispute over fraud.
This is by CNBC News.
According to the TV channel, within the framework of the agreements reached, Musk will have to leave the post of chairman of the board of directors of Tesla.
At the same time, the commission allowed Musk to retain the position of head of Tesla.
The founder of Tesla will also have to pay an administrative fine of $20 million.
The same amount will be charged to Tesla.
The money will be distributed among the affected investors.
In addition, the company will have to appoint two independent directors.
Elon Musk is an American entrepreneur who is on the list of the 50 richest people on the planet by Forbes magazine.
He is the head of space corporation SpaceX, neuroscience company Neuralink and the developer of electric cars Tesla, and the co-founder of Paypal.
The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission has filed a lawsuit against Tesla CEO Elon Musk over his tweet about the company’s possible ransom.
Last month, Musk announced plans to make Tesla a private company and buy back all shares on the stock exchange at a fixed price of $420.
The price of the $420 share was established allegedly "due to the significance of this number in the culture of marijuana," Bloomberg earlier with reference to the co-director of the security department of the commission Steven Pekin.
At the same time, Elon Musk subsequently abandoned his plans to buy out shares.
Commenting on the lawsuit filed against him by the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, the businessman said he considered the allegations of fraud unfounded, and added that he was very disappointed and saddened by these claims.
"Honesty is the most important value in my life, and the facts will prove that I have not violated it in any way," the businessman told CNBC.
In August, a group of Tesla shareholders filed a collective lawsuit against Musk, complaining about financial losses.
The plaintiffs claimed that the businessman’s posts brought them losses.
In particular, one of the shareholders said that the businessman’s tweets were misleading, causing Tesla stock sellers to buy securities at artificially overpriced prices to cover their positions.
Other plaintiffs also noted that Elon Musk’s careless statements led to sharp fluctuations in the course.
In September, Elon Musk also accused the head of the research company Citron Research.
Meanwhile, if Musk failed to settle his dispute with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, he would be threatened with removal from the management of the company and even jail.
This was stated by the former chairman of the commission, Harvey Pitt, to CNBC.
Musk is a “good guy who doesn’t know how to run a car company.”
