Kosachev: At the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly the topic of Russia in a negative key was practically absent
The head of the Federation Council Committee on International Affairs Konstantin Kosachev considers the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly successful for Russia and does not rule out that it can become a turning point in the perception of Russia as an integral participant in solving global world problems.
"The uniqueness of this 73rd session, in my opinion, lies in the fact that the rhetoric, to which we have almost become accustomed in recent years with regard to Russia, has now been somewhat more silenced," the senator said in an interview published on Sunday by the Russian newspaper.
He explained that in the previous years Russia was sometimes "designated as one of the three main threats to humanity, then along with Ebola fever, then along with climate change or terrorism, Russia was in this row, in any case, in the presentation of a group of Western countries, which on this matter was spoken quite unanimously".
At the 73rd session, Kosachev stressed, "the topic of Russia in the negative key was virtually absent."
"If you carefully analyze the speech of the President of the United States, the President of France, the speech of the Foreign Minister of Germany, I do not now take Ukraine, Georgia, or the British, in any case, the choir was not quite accurate," the politician paid attention, noting that Russia "was no longer a wall that is being trained with a tennis ball."
The head of the profile committee of the Federation Council does not rule out that this indicates a certain trend that, in his opinion, "will highlight the current session [of the UN General Assembly], although to the full extent this trend may be manifested in a year, two, three."
"I do not rule out that the current session in some sense may be turning point," Kosachev said, explaining that "too many examples of how with the connection of Russia it is possible to move forward in international affairs."
As an example, he cited the situation in Syria, around Iran and North Korea.
"So far, unfortunately, this is not Ukraine, but I have no doubt that the Russian vision of the Ukrainian crisis will also be in demand over time," he said.
This is due to the fact, he believes, that there is an “adequate, healthy perception of Russia as not just a possible – an integral participant in solving global problems of modern times.”
"I don't want to make a mistake, but I have the feeling that we are going somewhere to a point where movement will no longer be a move backwards, it will be a move forward," he added.
Another "interesting and important feeling" in this context Kosachev called the "request for the Russian vision of how the modern world should develop."
“I attended very many meetings of the head of the Russian delegation [at the session of the General Assembly] of the Minister of Foreign Affairs Sergei Lavrov, I held my own meetings, and I was very pleased to see that if a year or two or five years ago, Russian opinion, Russian vision of what is happening in the world, in large, nobody was interested, then now the situation is different,” – said the Chairman of the Committee of the Soviet Federation.
In his opinion, this is due to the fact that "the so-called new liberal order, which is embodied with the West, has no answers to the questions of how to solve world problems due to the obvious shortage of ideas in the global space, the shortage of ideas on how to solve the problems of the Middle East, the problem of terrorism, the problem of non-proliferation of nuclear weapons, the problem of migration."
"And here the request for the Russian vision is becoming more and more obvious," Kosachev expressed confidence, stressing that he considers in this sense that "this session is successful for the work of the Russian delegation, successful for Russia."
