ADH became the second most popular in Germany
The anti-immigrant "Alternative for Germany" is breaking another popularity record, and the ratings of Angela Merkel are falling.
It seems that German residents are seriously tired of Angela Merkel’s immigration policy, which has made the country a coveted target for millions of refugees from the Middle East.
Most clearly, this is stated by recent polls, according to which the anti-immigrant party "Alternative for Germany" is becoming more and more popular, and the positions of the ruling bloc of Merkel and Seehofer are weakening.
This week, ADG broke another record, rising to the second place in the popular sympathy ranking.
The right-wing Conservatives with 17 percent of popularity managed to bypass the Social Democrats, who have about 16 percent.
The gap of one percentage point can be attributed to a statistical error, but it cannot be ignored that the fact that the AdG created in 2013 from a small group of eurosceptic economists has managed to turn into a serious political force.
The leadership in the overall record for now continues to hold the ruling bloc of the CSU/CDU, which has about 30 percent.
However, there is a tendency to lose points here - even in April, the support of the bloc of Angela Merkel was four percentage points higher.
The personal rating of the German Chancellor, who is head of the German government for the fourth consecutive term, is also falling.
Today, 48 percent of Germans support Angela Merkel, which is 7 percent lower than last year.
Following the Social Democrats are the Greens (15%), the Left (11%) and the Liberals (10%).
The evolution of “alternatives”
The Alternative for Germany party was formed in September 2012 on the basis of the Alternative Choice 2013 group, which included members of the Christian Democratic Union.
The group initially opposed the government’s course, but initially dealt only with economic issues, including the problems of the euro and cooperation within the EU.
At the same time, the group opposed Germany's "sponsoring" of weak EU economies, did not rule out the possibility of a return to the German mark and a full exit of the country from the European Union.
With the deepening of the immigration crisis, the ADG political platform has expanded.
In 2013, the group formed into a full-fledged party that occupied a niche of eurosceptics and began to harshly criticize the government for the failure of immigration policy.
At the last parliamentary elections in 2017, the AdH managed to break into the Bundestag for the first time, receiving 94 seats (from 709).
Two representatives of Alternative for Germany have won seats in the European Parliament.
