The deadline of the universe
The universe will be around 140 billion years old, which is ten times the age of the observed world, which is about 13.8 billion years old.
The study of the international team of scientists is placed in the library of electronic preprints arXiv.org and sent for publication in the journal Publications of the Astronomical Society of Japan, reports the Japanese newspaper Asahi Shimbun.
The scientists came to this conclusion by using the Subaru Hyper Suprime-Cam (HSC) camera to observe about ten million galaxies.
Following the distribution of dark matter and dark energy, which account for more than 95 percent of the mass energy of the observed world, the scientists, working as part of the standard cosmological model ΛCDM (Λ Cold Dark Matter), estimated the rate of expansion of the universe, which was slightly slower than previously thought.
Subaru’s press release notes that the observations have provided a detailed three-dimensional map of the distribution of matter in the universe, and the data recording of the European space telescope Planck has clarified the limitations imposed on the ΛCDM parameters.
