About the possibility of a maritime blockade told the head of the U.S. Interior Department Ryan Zinke.
Contrary to international practice, the U.S. Department of Internal Affairs does not perform police, but civil functions, including the implementation of natural resources policy.
Therefore, Zinke’s statement came within the competence of the department he headed, although it was not deprived of political colour.
Speaking at an industrial event in Pittsburgh, Zinke said that thanks to the Navy, the U.S. controls maritime routes in the Middle East region and can block them if necessary.
According to Zinke, the need may be linked to Washington’s desire to hinder Russian supplies to the global energy market.
Zinke recalled that Russia still receives the lion’s share of its revenues from supplies to the world market of oil and gas.
The desire to distribute energy supplies in the Middle East as well as in Eastern Europe was the main motive for Moscow’s activation in this region, Zinke said.
The minister made it clear that the United States still expects to secure its leadership in the global energy market, becoming the largest supplier of oil and gas.
To do this, Washington will have to squeeze Russia and Iran, and the maritime blockade of trade routes is an acceptable measure on this path, Zinke believes.
