Macedonian opposition leader refuses to vote in referendum
Macedonia will hold a referendum on Sunday on the intergovernmental agreement with Greece to rename the Republic of Macedonia.
Citizens are asked to answer one question: "Do you support membership in the EU and NATO by accepting the agreement between the Republic of Macedonia and the Greek Republic?"
However, the leader of the leading opposition party "Interior Macedonian Revolutionary Organization - Democratic Party for Macedonian National Unity" (VMRO-DPMNE) Christian Mickoski said that he would not vote in the referendum.
As party spokesman Naum Stoilkovsky explained, Mickoski decided to abstain from voting to express his disagreement with the treaty, which he considers "dangerous".
According to the spokesman, the current referendum resolves the question of the country's name change and nothing more, while the party's strategic goal is to membership in NATO and the EU.
On September 30, Macedonian President Georgi Ivanov refused to participate in the referendum.
He explained that the name for the country he chose 27 years ago in a referendum on independence. the Macedonian leader considers the name change of the country a negative factor.
“A new semi-sovereign state with a new name is being created,” Ivanov said.
The agreement on the new official name of the former Yugoslav republic - the Republic of North Macedonia - was signed by the heads of foreign ministries of Macedonia and Greece on June 17 this year during a solemn ceremony on the shore of Lake Prespa, which crosses the border between the two countries.
This treaty should resolve the long-standing dispute over the name of the country, as well as Skopje’s path to NATO and the EU.
